I've been coming to DC annually since 1998 and I could kick myself for not finding this gem before. My boyfriend and I were searching for an Italian restaurant this evening and the ad by the Italians Kitchen caught our eye. It was amazing.  We had the Bella Napoli Bruschetta as an appetizer. The bread was crispy but not a severe crust where it would rip open your mouth on the first bite.  We followed it up with our entrees. He had the beef lasagna and I had the beef cannelloni. I stole a bite of his, it was delicious but mine put his to shame. I finished my whole dinner including the breadsticks. It was so fresh and perfect. The pasta is homemade and the sauce wasn't thin, wasn't too thick or chunky, it was perfection in a sauce.  We also had the Homemade Tiramisu. I don't care for Tiramisu because I don't like coffee. I enjoyed it. I'd recommend it without hesitation but with the caveat that it felt a little overpriced. I believe I got the "Italian" if I'm not mistaken. Very solid pie with pepperoni, sausage, bacon, pancetta and I think one other basically fancy bacon meat. Crust was just short of excellent (I live in Indiana (though I'm from California and spent 11 years in Seattle) and am unaware of any crust there I'd consider excellent). The side salad I got was simple but good, though they put on too much salad dressing. Ingredients were fresh and good. The vibe was laid back, the service was friendly. I typically rate things on where they fall on the price line on one axis and quality axis. The issue on my rating today is this: it's been years since I ate in this neighborhood or DC. I paid $24 for a 10" pizza and small salad and ice water. This seems a little high for an 8 out of 10 quality food place (and again, it's better than anything I'm aware of in the State of Indiana with the possible exception of a place in Bloomington, IN), at lunch that isn't costing extra for atmosphere. So given it felt a little pricy for lunch at a laid back place, and given it was the best pizza I've had in a while, but not among the truly great pizza places, I'm giving it 4/5 stars. Again, I'd highly recommend it. I'd just warn it's slightly over priced.

We dropped in on a whim and it was an excellent experience!  The management was great. There was another group there that had just received their pizzas. They ordered a pizza with mixed meats on top. Apparently they couldn't eat pork though they ordered pizzas with sausage on top. That was completely  their error and to me, it was up to them to pay for those pizzas and any other pizzas they may want to replace them with. Management was called in to resolve the problem. They wanted new pizzas, most likely at no charge, and the manager looked understandably a little perturbed but he ended up letting them order new pizzas.  I know that they say the customer is always right but they were most definitely wrong and the manager handled it very well.  After he took away their "unworthy" pizzas he went ahead and gave them to us at no charge. This all happened in the span of a few minutes and we had already put in our order. We wanted to cancel our order but still pay for it as a good gesture but their kitchen staff was too quick and our pizza was almost ready.  As far as taste, it was very good! I highly recommend supporting this family run restaurant.

We stopped by here for dinner while on vacation. It had a comfortable, cozy feel with rustic decor that was very fitting and wasn't tacky. The waitress was great, very pleasant and helpful even though they were extremely busy and she had to serve all the tables. There was no wait time at all, they had a constant flow of people but never got backed up. The food came out quite quickly after ordering and was DELICIOUS. Strongly recommend the Napolitano calzone. Will definitely come back if we are in the area again.

I had the fortune of living right next door to this terrific little restaurant for a couple years, and I loved it! The restaurant staff is extremely friendly and approachable; it's a long-standing local fixture filled with regulars, and it feels that way. I most recommend the Spinach Salad (killer goat cheese!), Caprese Salad, regular pepperoni pizza (can't go wrong!), the margherita pizza, and any of the paninis. The loaded up pizzas are excellent too, of course. It's a perfect spot for sitting outside, enjoying quality Italian and watching the world go by.

Its a great little place. Perfect for a comfortable evening out, with family / friends. No effort and comfy. I went to celebrate my birthday there, cos there were a number of kids with us. The wait time was about 45 mins, but then there were 11 of us, in a rather tiny place.  Food and drink: each pizza has a distinctive flavour - I like the veggie ones there. We had the Paradiso - 3 stars, the eggplant - 4 stars and the cheese - 3 stars. we got a bottle of wine for the grownups - brownie points to them, they have a cute winestopper and wine bottle bead decoration thing  :) for dessert, I would recommend the tiramisu cake - not for the ones who are tiramisu fanatics, but a well rounded tiramisu and cake. Dont get the chocolate cake - it was rather dry. The molten chocolate pie was delicious - just wish it was bigger!
